# MythosMUD Git Worktree Guidelines

> In the archives beneath Miskatonic, we do not experiment on the one true
> grimoire. We work from careful copies.

These rules define how we use **Git worktrees** with MythosMUD so that multiple
branches can be developed safely and predictably in parallel, without losing
track of which working copy belongs to which task.

## Goals

- **Consistent layout** for all MythosMUD worktrees.
- **Predictable naming** linking branches, worktree folders, and Cursor windows.
- **Low-risk workflow** that avoids accidental edits in the wrong tree.
- **Alignment with server rules** (only one server, started the right way).

## Directory Layout

- **Canonical repo** (primary worktree):
  - `f:/MythosMUD`
  - This is the root Git repository and should normally track `main` (or the
    long-lived integration branch you are working from).

- **Worktrees root** (sibling directory):
  - `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/`
  - Every additional worktree for MythosMUD lives under this directory.

- **Worktree folders**:
  - Pattern: `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/<kind>-<slug>`
  - `<kind>`: one of `feature`, `bugfix`, `refactor`, `spike`, `chore`.
  - `<slug>`: short, kebab-case description of the task, usually derived from
    the GitHub issue title or branch name.
  - Examples:
    - `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/feature-aggro`
    - `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/bugfix-client-message-desync`
    - `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/refactor-combat-logging`

## Branch Naming

Branches and worktrees should have matching, predictable names:

- **Branch name pattern**: `<kind>/<slug>`
  - Examples:
    - Branch: `feature/aggro`
    - Branch: `bugfix/npc-aggro-reset`
    - Branch: `refactor/combat-logging`

- **Branch ↔ worktree mapping**:
  - `feature/aggro` ↔ `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/feature-aggro`
  - `bugfix/npc-aggro-reset` ↔
    `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/bugfix-npc-aggro-reset`

This makes it trivial to see which directory belongs to which branch and task.

## Behavioral Conventions

- **One task per worktree**:
  - Treat each worktree as dedicated to a _single_ GitHub issue or clearly
    bounded task. Do not share a worktree across unrelated changes.

- **One Cursor window per worktree**:
  - Open each worktree path in its own Cursor window.
  - Do not reuse a Cursor window for a different worktree path once it has
    been created; close and reopen with the new path instead.

- **`.cursor/` isolation**:
  - Each worktree has its own `.cursor/` directory (plans, terminals, local
    settings).
  - Do **not** symlink or share `.cursor/` folders between worktrees.
  - Project-wide rules live in the repo and are shared via Git; local AI state
    is per-worktree.

- **Server rules**:
  - The **ONE SERVER ONLY RULE** still applies:
    - Never start more than one MythosMUD server at a time, even if you have
      multiple worktrees checked out.
    - Only start the server from the _active_ worktree for the task you are
      testing.
  - Always use `./scripts/stop_server.ps1` before switching which worktree
    owns the running server.

## Creating a New Worktree

When starting a new task:

1. Choose a kind and slug:
   - `kind`: `feature`, `bugfix`, `refactor`, `spike`, or `chore`.
   - `slug`: short, kebab-case description, usually based on the issue title.

2. Construct branch and path:
   - Branch: `<kind>/<slug>`
   - Worktree path: `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/<kind>-<slug>`

3. From the canonical repo (`f:/MythosMUD`):
   - For a **new** branch:
     - `git worktree add f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/<kind>-<slug> -b <kind>/<slug>`
   - For an **existing** branch:
     - `git worktree add f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/<kind>-<slug> <kind>/<slug>`

4. Open a new Cursor window rooted at the worktree path:
   - `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/<kind>-<slug>`

5. In the new worktree, create a task plan under `.cursor/plans/` for this
   task, following the standard worktree plan template
   (`.cursor/templates/worktree-plan-template.md`).

## Worktree Lifecycle

Treat each worktree as a lifecycle-bound artifact tied to a specific piece of
work.

### Create

- Create a worktree when:
  - You start work on a new feature, bugfix, refactor, spike, or chore that
    merits its own branch.
- Use the naming rules above to create:
  - A new branch on the canonical repo.
  - A new worktree under `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/`.
- Create a **worktree plan file** under `.cursor/plans/` that:
  - Captures the problem statement and context.
  - Lists todos for tests, implementation, docs, and cleanup.
  - Records the branch name and worktree path.

### Develop

- Perform all edits for the task inside the worktree that owns the branch.
- Keep the `.cursor/plans/` file up to date:
  - Update todos as you add tests, implement changes, and run validation.
  - Note any deviations or decisions that affect the task.
- Only start the server from this worktree when testing this task.
- Follow MythosMUD rules about full-stack changes (server, client,
  persistence) where applicable.

### Review and Merge

- Use the worktree to prepare commits and open a PR from the branch to the
  appropriate base (`main`, `develop`, or the configured integration branch).
- During review:
  - Keep any follow-up investigation or small review fixes in the _same_
    branch and worktree until the PR is accepted.
  - If review feedback fundamentally changes scope, consider:
    - Closing the worktree after merging, and
    - Opening a new branch/worktree for the new scope.

### Cleanup

After a branch has been merged or abandoned:

- From the canonical repo (`f:/MythosMUD`), remove the worktree:
  - `git worktree remove f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/<kind>-<slug>`
- Ensure the directory is gone or manually delete it if Git left an empty
  folder.
- If the branch is no longer needed:
  - Clean up the branch with the appropriate `git branch -d` / `-D` behavior.

**Do not** keep stale worktrees around indefinitely; they become easy to
confuse and clutter local disk, `.cursor/` state, and terminal history.

### Weekly Cleanup Checklist

At least once per week (or before starting a new major task), reconcile your
local worktrees:

- From `f:/MythosMUD`:
  - `git worktree list` to see all registered worktrees.
- For each entry:
  - Confirm whether the corresponding branch has been merged or abandoned.
  - If so, remove the worktree and (optionally) delete the branch.
- Optionally, keep a short note in `TASKS.local.md` about which worktrees you
  expect to be active this week.

## Guardrails and Safety

- **Do not edit the same feature from multiple worktrees at once.**
  - Pick one worktree per logical piece of work to avoid diverging local
    copies and confusing branch history.

- **Never create a worktree inside `.git/` or another worktree.**
  - All MythosMUD worktrees belong **only** under:
    - `f:/MythosMUD`
    - `f:/MythosMUD-worktrees/`

- **Respect server and test rules in all worktrees**:
  - Only one MythosMUD server running at any given time.
  - Always run tests from the project root of the active worktree, using the
    prescribed `make`/PowerShell scripts.

- **Do not share `.cursor/` state** between worktrees:
  - No symlinks or manual copying of `.cursor/` directories.
  - Rules and skills live in Git; each worktree’s AI state is ephemeral and
    local to that branch’s work.
